1
00:02:34,322 --> 00:02:36,283
Hello, stranger.

2
00:03:11,484 --> 00:03:13,695
Sorry. Looking for a cigarette.

3
00:03:14,613 --> 00:03:15,947
I've given up.

4
00:03:18,658 --> 00:03:19,993
Thank you.

5
00:03:22,329 --> 00:03:24,581
- Got to be somewhere?
- Work.

6
00:03:26,124 --> 00:03:28,084
You didn't fancy my sandwiches?

7
00:03:28,209 --> 00:03:30,837
- Don't eat fish.
- Why not?

8
00:03:31,713 --> 00:03:33,423
Fish piss in the sea.

9
00:03:33,924 --> 00:03:36,760
- So do children.
- Don't eat children, either.

10
00:03:38,053 --> 00:03:39,554
What's your work?

11
00:03:39,638 --> 00:03:41,806
I'm sort of a journalist.

12
00:03:42,140 --> 00:03:44,976
- What sort?
- I write obituaries.

13
00:03:56,947 --> 00:03:59,115
Are we in for a long wait?

14
00:04:01,201 --> 00:04:03,328
She was 21 when she came in.

15
00:04:05,705 --> 00:04:07,207
Does it hurt?

16
00:04:07,916 --> 00:04:09,251
I'll live.

17
00:04:10,377 --> 00:04:12,837
Do you want me to put your leg up?

18
00:04:12,879 --> 00:04:14,464
Yes, please.

19
00:04:29,271 --> 00:04:31,273
Who cut off your crusts?

20
00:04:31,731 --> 00:04:32,691
Me.

21
00:04:32,774 --> 00:04:35,694
Did your mother cut off your crusts
when you were a little boy?

22
00:04:35,777 --> 00:04:39,155
- Yes, I believe she did.
- You should eat your crusts.

23
00:04:39,531 --> 00:04:41,408
You should stop smoking.

24
00:04:42,951 --> 00:04:44,452
How long was I out?

25
00:04:44,536 --> 00:04:47,080
- About 10 seconds.
- Then what?

26
00:04:48,373 --> 00:04:50,333
You came to. You focused on me.

27
00:04:50,417 --> 00:04:53,128
You said, "Hello, stranger."

28
00:04:53,211 --> 00:04:54,754
What a floozy.

29
00:04:54,838 --> 00:04:58,675
The cabbie crossed himself, he went,
"Thank fuck. I thought I'd killed her."

30
00:04:58,758 --> 00:05:01,094
I said, "Let's get her to a hospital."
He hesitated.

31
00:05:01,177 --> 00:05:04,472
I think he thought there'd be paperwork
and he'd be held responsible.

32
00:05:04,556 --> 00:05:08,018
So I said with a slight sneer,
"Please just drop us at the hospital."

33
00:05:08,059 --> 00:05:09,686
Show me the sneer.

34
00:05:10,604 --> 00:05:12,564
Very good, buster.

35
00:05:13,648 --> 00:05:15,150
Thank you.

36
00:05:23,950 --> 00:05:26,202
- I told you, I've given up.
- Try harder.

37
00:05:26,286 --> 00:05:27,829
You live here?

38
00:05:28,246 --> 00:05:30,415
Just arrived from New York.

39
00:05:31,124 --> 00:05:33,084
Taking a vacation?

40
00:05:33,126 --> 00:05:35,045
I'm on an expedition.

41
00:05:35,670 --> 00:05:37,464
Where's your baggage?

42
00:05:38,632 --> 00:05:41,343
- Where are you staying?
- I'm a waif.

43
00:05:43,970 --> 00:05:45,472
A red bus.

44
00:05:47,223 --> 00:05:51,561
Policeman or "bobby."
Observe the distinctive helmet.

45
00:05:53,188 --> 00:05:55,732
Saint Paul's Cathedral.
Please note the famous dome.

46
00:05:55,815 --> 00:05:59,611
- This is a truly magnificent tour.
- It's the London tourists never get to see.

47
00:05:59,694 --> 00:06:02,530
- What's this?
- I've no idea.

48
00:06:23,301 --> 00:06:27,055
They're all people
who died saving the lives of others.

49
00:06:28,723 --> 00:06:30,642
I've been here before.

50
00:06:40,235 --> 00:06:43,071
Twenty years ago, we came here.

51
00:06:44,322 --> 00:06:48,285
My mother's dead. My father and I came here
the afternoon she died.

52
00:06:50,036 --> 00:06:53,748
She was a smoker.
She died in the hospital, actually.

53
00:06:53,832 --> 00:06:56,543
- Is your father still alive?
- Hanging on.

54
00:06:57,002 --> 00:06:58,295
He's in a home.

55
00:06:58,920 --> 00:07:02,173
- You're late for work.
- You saying you want me to go?

56
00:07:02,257 --> 00:07:04,175
I'm saying you're late for work.

57
00:07:04,884 --> 00:07:07,429
How did you end up writing obituaries?

58
00:07:07,721 --> 00:07:11,850
Well, I had dreams of being a writer,
but I had no voice.

59
00:07:12,517 --> 00:07:14,853
What am I saying? I had no talent.

60
00:07:14,936 --> 00:07:19,190
So I ended up in obituaries,
which is the Siberia of journalism.

61
00:07:19,441 --> 00:07:23,153
Tell me what you do.
I want to imagine you in Siberia.

62
00:07:23,194 --> 00:07:24,529
Really?

63
00:07:27,449 --> 00:07:30,285
We call it "the obits page."

64
00:07:31,328 --> 00:07:34,164
There's three of us: me, Graham, and Harry.

65
00:07:34,748 --> 00:07:38,877
When I get to work, without fail...
Are you sure you want to know?

66
00:07:39,920 --> 00:07:44,049
Well, if someone important died,
we go to the "deep freeze"...

67
00:07:47,510 --> 00:07:51,014
which is a computer file...

68
00:07:51,097 --> 00:07:54,392
with all the obituaries,
and we find the dead person's life.

69
00:07:54,434 --> 00:07:57,103
People's obituaries are written
while they're still alive?

70
00:07:57,187 --> 00:07:58,772
Some people's.

71
00:07:59,356 --> 00:08:02,400
Then Harry, he's the editor,
decides who we'll lead with.

72
00:08:02,484 --> 00:08:04,694
Then we make calls, check facts.

73
00:08:04,778 --> 00:08:09,324
At 6:00, we stand around the computer
and look at the next day's page...

74
00:08:10,116 --> 00:08:12,410
and make final changes.

75
00:08:12,786 --> 00:08:15,580
Add a few euphemisms
for our own amusement.

76
00:08:15,622 --> 00:08:16,957
Such as?

77
00:08:19,251 --> 00:08:23,421
"He was a convivial fellow."
Meaning he was an alcoholic.

78
00:08:24,214 --> 00:08:27,592
"He valued his privacy." Gay.

79
00:08:28,093 --> 00:08:30,845
"He enjoyed his privacy." Raging queen.

80
00:08:32,055 --> 00:08:34,099
What would my euphemism be?

81
00:08:35,100 --> 00:08:38,061
- "She was disarming."
- That's not a euphemism.

82
00:08:38,979 --> 00:08:40,438
Yes, it is.

83
00:08:49,447 --> 00:08:52,367
- What were you doing in New York?
- You know.

84
00:08:55,495 --> 00:08:59,916
Well, no, I don't. What, were you studying?

85
00:09:00,083 --> 00:09:01,376
Stripping.

86
00:09:02,836 --> 00:09:05,088
Look at your little eyes.

87
00:09:06,172 --> 00:09:08,049
I can't see my little eyes.

88
00:09:13,471 --> 00:09:14,973
Why did you leave?

89
00:09:15,599 --> 00:09:17,601
Problems with a male.

90
00:09:17,851 --> 00:09:19,519
- Boyfriend?
- Kind of.

91
00:09:20,687 --> 00:09:22,939
And you left him, just like that?

92
00:09:23,023 --> 00:09:27,027
It's the only way to leave.
"I don't love you anymore. Goodbye."

93
00:09:27,110 --> 00:09:30,322
- Supposing you do still love them?
- You don't leave.

94
00:09:31,156 --> 00:09:34,326
- You've never left somebody you still love?
- No.

95
00:09:38,204 --> 00:09:39,789
This is me.

96
00:09:46,212 --> 00:09:47,839
Enjoy your stay.

97
00:09:49,215 --> 00:09:52,344
Please remember
our traffic tends to come from the right.

98
00:09:54,137 --> 00:09:55,221
Bye.

99
00:10:08,068 --> 00:10:09,945
Do you have a girlfriend?

100
00:10:10,320 --> 00:10:11,655
Yeah. Ruth.

101
00:10:12,238 --> 00:10:15,200
She's called Ruth. She's a linguist.

102
00:10:16,576 --> 00:10:18,745
- What's your name?
- Alice.

103
00:10:19,913 --> 00:10:22,332
My name is Alice Ayres.

104
00:10:29,339 --> 00:10:30,507
Good.

105
00:10:30,590 --> 00:10:33,760
I'm just gonna change the film.
Are you okay for time?

106
00:10:37,931 --> 00:10:40,558
- Do you mind if I smoke?
- lf you must.

107
00:10:41,726 --> 00:10:44,271
- I don't have to.
- Then don't.

108
00:10:56,408 --> 00:10:58,076
I liked your book.

109
00:10:58,994 --> 00:11:00,161
Thanks.

110
00:11:02,080 --> 00:11:04,958
- When's it published?
- Next year. How come you've read it?

111
00:11:05,041 --> 00:11:08,253
Your publisher sent me a manuscript.
I read it last night.

112
00:11:08,878 --> 00:11:10,797
You kept me up till 4:00.

113
00:11:11,840 --> 00:11:13,091
I'm flattered.

114
00:11:13,466 --> 00:11:15,927
Is your heroine
based on someone you know?

115
00:11:16,511 --> 00:11:18,680
Yes. She's someone called Alice.

116
00:11:19,180 --> 00:11:21,683
How does she feel
about you stealing her life?

117
00:11:21,766 --> 00:11:23,226
Borrowing her life.

118
00:11:23,351 --> 00:11:25,937
I'm dedicating the book to her.
She's pleased.

119
00:11:34,863 --> 00:11:36,239
Do you exhibit?

120
00:11:36,323 --> 00:11:39,200
Sometimes. I have a thing next year.

121
00:11:45,206 --> 00:11:46,541
Portraits?

122
00:11:48,627 --> 00:11:51,212
- Of who?
- Strangers.

123
00:11:54,174 --> 00:11:57,677
How do your strangers feel
about you stealing their lives?

124
00:11:57,844 --> 00:11:59,262
Borrowing.

125
00:12:00,805 --> 00:12:02,182
Am I a stranger?

126
00:12:03,141 --> 00:12:04,809
No. You're a job.

127
00:12:06,728 --> 00:12:08,772
And you're a sloucher. Sit up.

128
00:12:15,445 --> 00:12:16,905
You didn't find it obscene?

129
00:12:16,988 --> 00:12:18,573
- What?
- The book.

130
00:12:19,908 --> 00:12:22,035
I thought it was accurate.

131
00:12:22,661 --> 00:12:24,162
About what?

132
00:12:24,412 --> 00:12:26,748
About sex. About love.

133
00:12:27,082 --> 00:12:28,500
In what way?

134
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:32,170
- You wrote it.
- You read it till 4:00.

135
00:12:32,504 --> 00:12:35,590
Don't raise your eyebrows.
It makes you look smug.

136
00:12:43,890 --> 00:12:47,185
- But you did like it?
- Yes, but I could go off it.

137
00:12:53,608 --> 00:12:54,943
Stand up.

138
00:13:01,241 --> 00:13:03,034
Any criticisms?

139
00:13:04,661 --> 00:13:06,204
I'm not sure about the title.

140
00:13:06,288 --> 00:13:07,831
Got a better one?

141
00:13:08,790 --> 00:13:10,250
<i>The Aquarium.</i>

142
00:13:11,251 --> 00:13:13,003
So you liked the filth.

143
00:13:13,336 --> 00:13:16,047
- You like aquariums.
- Fish are therapeutic.

144
00:13:16,131 --> 00:13:18,508
- Hang out in aquariums, do you?
- When I can.

145
00:13:18,550 --> 00:13:20,385
Good for picking up strangers?

146
00:13:20,468 --> 00:13:22,804
Photographing strangers.

147
00:13:32,439 --> 00:13:33,773
Come here.

148
00:13:51,082 --> 00:13:52,751
You're beautiful.

149
00:14:00,425 --> 00:14:02,761
I don't kiss strange men.

150
00:14:03,136 --> 00:14:04,638
Neither do I.

151
00:15:16,001 --> 00:15:18,670
Do you and this Alice live together?

152
00:15:23,466 --> 00:15:24,801
Yes.

153
00:15:36,354 --> 00:15:37,731
Are you married?

154
00:15:37,814 --> 00:15:39,149
Yes.

155
00:15:39,357 --> 00:15:41,985
- No. Yes.
- Which?

156
00:15:42,319 --> 00:15:43,987
Separated.

157
00:15:44,613 --> 00:15:46,239
- Do you have any children?
- No.

158
00:15:46,323 --> 00:15:49,326
- Would you like some?
- Yes, but not today.

159
00:15:50,035 --> 00:15:52,370
Would Alice like children?

160
00:15:53,413 --> 00:15:54,956
She's too young.

161
00:15:56,166 --> 00:15:59,669
She works in a café near here.
She's coming to meet me.

162
00:16:00,420 --> 00:16:01,838
Quite soon.

163
00:16:04,507 --> 00:16:06,843
Why are you wasting her time?

164
00:16:07,969 --> 00:16:10,805
- You're judgmental.
- You're devious.

165
00:16:10,889 --> 00:16:14,559
I'm not wasting her time.
She's completely lovable.

166
00:16:14,643 --> 00:16:16,478
And completely unleavable.

167
00:16:16,561 --> 00:16:20,565
And you don't want someone else
getting their dirty hands on her.

168
00:16:20,690 --> 00:16:22,692
- Men are crap.
- But all the same...

169
00:16:22,776 --> 00:16:24,402
They're still crap.

170
00:16:26,196 --> 00:16:27,364
Your muse.

171
00:16:29,741 --> 00:16:32,702
- You've ruined my life.
- You'll get over it.

172
00:16:41,253 --> 00:16:42,420
Dan.

173
00:16:44,714 --> 00:16:46,049
Your shirt.

174
00:16:57,477 --> 00:16:59,187
You all done?

175
00:16:59,729 --> 00:17:02,357
- How's the photographer?
- Good. Professional.

176
00:17:03,358 --> 00:17:05,735
Rigorous. Beady. One of your lot.

177
00:17:05,777 --> 00:17:08,029
<i>- What, female?
- Americano.</i>

178
00:17:12,284 --> 00:17:13,618
Come on.

179
00:17:23,169 --> 00:17:24,421
Anna?

180
00:17:29,134 --> 00:17:30,802
- Alice.
- Hi.

181
00:17:30,885 --> 00:17:33,888
- Sorry to interrupt.
- No, we've just finished.

182
00:17:34,472 --> 00:17:36,516
- Would you like some tea?
- No, thanks.

183
00:17:36,600 --> 00:17:39,394
I've been serving it all day.
Can I use your loo?

184
00:17:39,477 --> 00:17:41,396
Sure. Just through there.

185
00:17:48,987 --> 00:17:50,280
She is beautiful.

186
00:17:50,322 --> 00:17:52,407
- I've got to see you.
- No.

187
00:17:52,866 --> 00:17:54,451
What's this? Patriotism?

188
00:17:54,492 --> 00:17:56,328
- I don't want trouble.
- I'm not trouble.

189
00:17:56,411 --> 00:17:57,829
You're taken.

190
00:17:59,956 --> 00:18:01,666
- I've got to see you.
- Tough.

191
00:18:01,750 --> 00:18:04,419
- You kissed me.
- What are you, 12?

192
00:18:07,797 --> 00:18:10,091
I'm a block of ice.

193
00:18:13,428 --> 00:18:15,221
Will you take my photo?

194
00:18:15,305 --> 00:18:18,016
I've never been photographed
by a professional before.

195
00:18:18,058 --> 00:18:20,644
I'd really appreciate it. I can pay you.

196
00:18:20,727 --> 00:18:22,479
No, I'd like to.

197
00:18:22,896 --> 00:18:24,731
Only if you don't mind.

198
00:18:25,357 --> 00:18:26,524
Why should I?

199
00:18:26,608 --> 00:18:28,610
Because you'll have to go away.

200
00:18:28,693 --> 00:18:31,529
We don't want him here
while we're working, do we?

201
00:18:31,696 --> 00:18:33,156
No, we don't.

202
00:18:36,201 --> 00:18:38,370
Right. I'll be in the pub on the corner.

203
00:18:38,453 --> 00:18:39,704
Have fun.

204
00:18:42,916 --> 00:18:44,251
Thank you.

205
00:18:44,584 --> 00:18:47,879
- Good luck with your exhibition.
- Good luck with your book.

206
00:19:03,395 --> 00:19:05,563
So you've got an exhibition?

207
00:19:06,523 --> 00:19:07,691
Yeah.

208
00:19:12,237 --> 00:19:14,072
I read Dan's book.

209
00:19:15,156 --> 00:19:17,951
You've had quite a life.

210
00:19:19,411 --> 00:19:20,745
Thanks.

211
00:19:26,793 --> 00:19:28,962
He said you work in a café?

212
00:19:29,087 --> 00:19:30,922
